{
  "texts": [
    "Early work on data poisoning focused on attacks against SVMs (Biggio et al., 2012), with later efforts extending to DNNs by introducing adversarial noise to key training examples (Koh and Liang, 2017).",
    "However, these attacks often result in small performance drops and produce easily detectable poisoned examples (Muñoz-González et al., 2017; Yang et al., 2017).",
    "Another form of data poisoning is backdoor attacks, where we embed trigger patterns in the data to induce model failures when triggered while leaving performance on clean data unaffected (Chen et al., 2017; Liu et al., 2020; Wan et al., 2023a).",
    "Despite their stealth, they are less suited for preventing data exploitation, as they don't hinder overall test accuracy (Barni et al., 2019).",
    "Unlearnable dataset."
  ]
}